The paper deals with optimization algorithms for sparse signal recovery, which is a problem that is relevant to several sub-fields of computer science. However, the focus on sparsity-constrained optimization and the use of algorithms such as Orthogonal Matching Pursuit and Frank-Wolfe suggest that the paper is most likely to be classified under the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. The paper also involves the use of randomization and multi-armed bandit algorithms, which are techniques that are commonly used in Information Theory (cs.IT) and Data Structures (cs.DS) respectively. Theoretical analysis of the algorithms involves the use of numerical analysis and optimization techniques, which are relevant to the Numerical Analysis (cs.NA) sub-category. Finally, the paper's focus on optimization algorithms suggests that it may also be classified under the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category.
